text: Donate to Lisa McClain for Congress Today! I am a Conservative Outsider with a proven success record as a business leader, and that is EXACTLY what Congress needs. My goal is to restore the quality of life to the citizens of Michigan. I will work to support a dynamic U.S. economy, where thriving businesses create jobs and opportunity. I will work to ensure a strong national defense and effective law enforcement that balances liberty and safety – instead of ineffective authoritarianism which puts freedom and security at risk. I believe in the role of government as a force for good. It can, and should, uphold and protect its citizens’ lives, liberty and property. I believe that government should be closer to the people, not further away. The more we trust people, the stronger we, and society become. I will always provide the citizens of Michigan with honest and ethical representation.

Donate to Lisa McClain for Congress Today!

 I am a Conservative Outsider with a proven success record as a business leader, and that is EXACTLY what Congress needs.  My goal is to restore the quality of life to the citizens of Michigan.

  • I believe that government should be closer to the people, not further away. The more we trust people, the stronger we, and society become. 
  • I will always provide the citizens of Michigan with honest and ethical representation.

name: Kim Reynolds For Iowa
text: Meet Kim. Kim Reynolds understands the challenges families face because she’s faced them herself. A fifth-generation Iowan, she grew up in a working-class family in St. Charles, Iowa. A recognized leader in state and local issues, Kim served as county treasurer and state senator before becoming Lieutenant Governor and Governor.As Lt. Governor, she served as the chairwoman of the National Lt. Governors Association. In this role, she led nationwide discussions on policy, economic development, and issues affecting states across the country. Kim has made Iowa a national leader in STEM education; and she’s led economic development trade missions to China, Germany, South Korea, Vietnam, the Philippines and Thailand, working towards increased exports, more foreign direct investment and new jobs for Iowa. Throughout her entire life, Kim Reynolds has never forgotten her working class roots. As a teenager she worked as a waitress at Younkers, and later as a checker at Hy-Vee all while raising a young family and getting her college degree. That’s why her top priorities as governor are creating good-paying jobs, cutting taxes, investing in public schools, and increasing opportunity in every part of Iowa. Kim and her husband, “First Dude” Kevin, have been married 36 years, have three daughters and nine grandchildren.

name: McCuskey For West Virginia
text: We’re cleaning up West Virginia! As your State Auditor, I’ve worked every day to protect your tax dollars from waste, fraud, and abuse. Any dollar wasted is a one that we’ve stolen from the people of West Virginia. That’s why I’ve spent the last two and a half years working to fight these problems, and the good news is we’ve had a lot of success. Here’s what one of the state’s leading papers had to say about our efforts. “The state of West Virginia often seems to rank on the top of the list for bad measures and at the bottom for good ones, but State Auditor J.B. McCuskey and his staff have changed one critical ranking. West Virginia is one of two states to receive an A Plus grade for its government spending transparency website in the latest report by the United States Public Interest Research Group released Wednesday.” -The Daily Mail, April 28, 2018 I’ve worked hard to uphold our shared commonsense conservative principles, but the job is not done. That’s why I am running for re-election as State Auditor. It is also why I need your help. I have a simple philosophy: government should tax as little as possible from people and spend every penny it does have on programs that help the people of our state. This may sound like commonsense to you and me, but many special interests in Charleston think the money should be theirs to spend in the darkness. So, if you agree with me, please consider sending a contribution today to my campaign. I have attached an envelope and reply card for you to fill out. I would be honored to have your support, and I am going to need it to make sure I can keep fighting for you in Charleston.

We’re cleaning up West Virginia! As your State Auditor, I’ve worked every day to protect your tax dollars from waste, fraud, and abuse. Any dollar wasted is a one that we’ve stolen from the people of West Virginia.

That’s why I’ve spent the last two and a half years working to fight these problems, and the good news is we’ve had a lot of success. Here’s what one of the state’s leading papers had to say about our efforts.

“The state of West Virginia often seems to rank on the top of the list for bad measures and at the bottom for good ones, but State Auditor J.B. McCuskey and his staff have changed one critical ranking.

West Virginia is one of two states to receive an A Plus grade for its government spending transparency website in the latest report by the United States Public Interest Research Group released Wednesday.”

-The Daily Mail, April 28, 2018

I’ve worked hard to uphold our shared commonsense conservative principles, but the job is not done. That’s why I am running for re-election as State Auditor. It is also why I need your help.

I have a simple philosophy: government should tax as little as possible from people and spend every penny it does have on programs that help the people of our state. This may sound like commonsense to you and me, but many special interests in Charleston think the money should be theirs to spend in the darkness.

So, if you agree with me, please consider sending a contribution today to my campaign. I have attached an envelope and reply card for you to fill out. 

I would be honored to have your support, and I am going to need it to make sure I can keep fighting for you in Charleston.

My background is 20 years in Corporate America and Startups, with a decade working with NPOs and Interfaith groups. Post COVID, we are going to need the leader that has shown they are willing to first respond, as well as able to get work done in Albany. We will have bi-partisanship and cooperation. Also, By rule, we can focus on our constituents and meet in a town hall fashion, to build from this and continue to solve issues.

name: Friends Of Senator Jane Nelson
text: Donate to Texas Senator Jane Nelson Today! Texas State Senator Jane Nelson, R-Flower Mound, is known for her tireless commitment to her constituents and her ability to get things done. A businesswoman, former teacher, and proud mother and grandmother, she brings her real-world experience to tackling some of the most pressing problems facing the state. She is currently the Chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, and is the first woman in Texas legislative history to chair a standing budget-writing committee. She is also the highest-ranking Republican in the Senate. Before becoming Chairman of the Finance Committee, she was the longest-serving Chairman of the Health and Human Services Committee. As Chair of Senate Finance, Senator Nelson has authored three consecutive balanced budgets that increase funding for public education and invest in critical infrastructure, while still cutting taxes and reducing wasteful spending. Her work on behalf of abused children, seniors, cancer survivors, domestic abuse victims and people with disabilities has earned her widespread recognition.

name: Friends Of Eric Wimberger
text: Eric Wimberger was born and raised in DePere. After high school, he attended St. Cloud State University. Active in student affairs, he was the student body president before receiving a bachelor’s degree in criminal justice. He then drove orange semi-trucks for a local trucking company long haul, logging more than 120k safe miles before enrolling at Marquette University Law School. With his Juris Doctor, Eric Wimberger was commissioned in the United States Marine Corps as a Judge Advocate where he honed his legal skills. He was stationed mostly in Japan and Washington D.C., honorably discharging as a Captain. Duty assignments included Senior Defense Counsel at Marine Corps Air Station, Iwakuni, Senior Legal Assistance Officer at Marine Corps Air Station, Iwakuni, and Attorney Adviser for the Department of the Navy Physical Evaluation Board in Washington, D.C. Home in 2010, Eric Wimberger opened his law practice, diligently representing his clients for the ends of justice as a “Super Lawyer Rising Star.” Eric Wimberger remains dedicated to making a positive difference in the community. When not developing his law practice, he serves on the philanthropic Cloud Family Foundation as a board member. You can also find him often helping his mom make great family memories at her small business, Sweet Memories Candy Shoppe, in Lakewood. Donate to Wimberger for State Senate Today!

name: Vote Bolick
text: Shawnna L.M. Bolick is a wife, mother and an education advocate. Most recently, Bolick was appointed to the Arizona State Board of Education’s Academic Standards Development Committee as a public high school parent as well as an appointee to Arizona’s Early Childhood Education and Health Board by Governor Doug Ducey. Bolick graduated from Syracuse University’s Maxwell School of Citizenship and Public Affairs with a B.A. in policy studies. After she graduated from Syracuse University, Shawnna returned to the DC area upon graduation from the Maxwell School to complete her Masters coursework from American University. Shawnna is no stranger to the inner workings of state government. She interned in the New York State Assembly one semester as an undergraduate and after completing her graduate coursework she moved to Austin, TX where she worked for then Texas Lt. Governor Rick Perry on his high-tech council. In May 2004, Shawnna published her first book titled Playtime in Phoenix: The Ultimate Guide to Learning & Having Fun with Kids! She is a Republican precinct committeeman and state committeeman, and once served as program director for the Paradise Valley Republican Women’s Club. She continues to be engaged in grassroots organizing. Bolick has been involved in GOP grassroots efforts since the 1990s starting as a College Republican at Syracuse University. Shawnna has immersed herself in community affairs including Moms Offering Moms Support – MOMs Club International; her children's Parent Teacher Organization (PTO); Syracuse University Alumni Club of Arizona (SUACA); Mothers of Preschoolers (MOPS) at La Casa de Cristo; Moms and More and Moms Next at La Casa de Cristo; the Children’s Advocacy Center; and BASIS Phoenix Boosters. Shawnna was elected in 2018 and currently serving her first term. Shawnna and her family reside in Phoenix, AZ. Donate to Bolick for Arizona Today!
description:
Shawnna L.M. Bolick is a wife, mother and an education advocate.  

 

Most recently, Bolick was appointed to the Arizona State Board of Education’s Academic Standards Development Committee as a public high school parent as well as an appointee to Arizona’s Early Childhood Education and Health Board by Governor Doug Ducey.

 

Bolick graduated from Syracuse University’s Maxwell School of Citizenship and Public Affairs with a B.A. in policy studies.  After she graduated from Syracuse University, Shawnna returned to the DC area upon graduation from the Maxwell School to complete her Masters coursework from American University. 

 

Shawnna is no stranger to the inner workings of state government. She interned in the New York State Assembly one semester as an undergraduate and after completing her graduate coursework she moved to Austin, TX where she worked for then Texas Lt. Governor Rick Perry on his high-tech council.  

 

In May 2004, Shawnna published her first book titled Playtime in Phoenix: The Ultimate Guide to Learning & Having Fun with Kids! 

 

She is a Republican precinct committeeman and state committeeman, and once served as program director for the Paradise Valley Republican Women’s Club. She continues to be engaged in grassroots organizing. Bolick has been involved in GOP grassroots efforts since the 1990s starting as a College Republican at Syracuse University.   

 

Shawnna has immersed herself in community affairs including Moms Offering Moms Support – MOMs Club International; her children's Parent Teacher Organization (PTO); Syracuse University Alumni Club of Arizona (SUACA); Mothers of Preschoolers (MOPS) at La Casa de Cristo; Moms and More and Moms Next at La Casa de Cristo; the Children’s Advocacy Center; and BASIS Phoenix Boosters.

 

Shawnna was elected in 2018 and currently serving her first term. Shawnna and her family reside in Phoenix, AZ.

name: Crowe For Georgia
text: Working Together for a Better Georgia My name is Clint Crowe and I appreciate your support as I seek election to the Georgia House of Representatives for the 110th District. I believe I have a unique and varied background which gives me a vast amount of experience that will be beneficial in this role. As a small business owner and entrepreneur, I am committed to not only keeping Georgia the number one place to do business but also the number one place to start a business because small business is the backbone of our economy. According to the Georgia Department of Labor, 99.7% of business establishments in Georgia are categorized as small (fewer than 500 employees). I know what resources and environments are best for the development and operation of these businesses. As a Realtor, and having been involved with economic development for many years as a member of the Butts County Planning and Zoning Commission, as well as the Development Authority, I understand that private property rights and good, quality, well thought out economic development are essential to a vibrant and healthy community. I am committed to preserving private property rights, as well as focusing on bringing beneficial and job creating projects to our region. And lastly, as a former law enforcement officer, I understand that these first two areas are unimportant if we do not have safe and secure neighborhoods to live in and raise our families. Unfortunately, crime is not going down and the members of our law enforcement community are our sworn defenders who risk themselves to protect us from those who seek to do us harm. I know what they need to help them do their job and I can have a unique input on the creation of laws that are both easier to enforce and beneficial for everyone. I am fully invested in making sure we do all we can to protect them and show our appreciation for their sacrifices and service. Thank you again for your support and I am honored to have the opportunity to serve the people of our community at the Capitol.
description:
Working Together for a Better Georgia

My name is Clint Crowe and I appreciate your support as I seek election to the Georgia House of Representatives for the 110th District. I believe I have a unique and varied background which gives me a vast amount of experience that will be beneficial in this role.

As a small business owner and entrepreneur, I am committed to not only keeping Georgia the number one place to do business but also the number one place to start a business because small business is the backbone of our economy. According to the Georgia Department of Labor, 99.7% of business establishments in Georgia are categorized as small (fewer than 500 employees). I know what resources and environments are best for the development and operation of these businesses.

As a Realtor, and having been involved with economic development for many years as a member of the Butts County Planning and Zoning Commission, as well as the Development Authority, I understand that private property rights and good, quality, well thought out economic development are essential to a vibrant and healthy community.  I am committed to preserving private property rights, as well as focusing on bringing beneficial and job creating projects to our region.

And lastly, as a former law enforcement officer, I understand that these first two areas are unimportant if we do not have safe and secure neighborhoods to live in and raise our families. Unfortunately, crime is not going down and the members of our law enforcement community are our sworn defenders who risk themselves to protect us from those who seek to do us harm. I know what they need to help them do their job and I can have a unique input on the creation of laws that are both easier to enforce and beneficial for everyone. I am fully invested in making sure we do all we can to protect them and show our appreciation for their sacrifices and service.

Thank you again for your support and I am honored to have the opportunity to serve the people of our community at the Capitol.

name: Chilton For Iowa
text: Pauline Chilton, the daughter of a Vietnam veteran, wife of a Gulf War veteran, grew up in Chicago and has been proud to call Dubuque home for the last 18 years. After graduating from Kenwood Academy, one of Chicago's three magnet schools, she attended Beloit College. During her academic career, she enjoyed studying chemistry, biochemistry, German, Japanese, and Brazilian Portuguese. She worked on her own chemistry research with the privilege of using facilities at the University of Chicago and Argonne National Laboratory. She was granted numerous awards and scholarships for participating in academic competitions and her work in chemistry. She did an internship in a biochemistry laboratory at Rush Presbyterian Medical Center. A full time Realtor, Pauline has the perfect combination of the Midwestern attitude of hard work and dedication along with big city tenacity in order to facilitate smooth transactions for her clients. She feels that her real estate career has helped her to understand the needs of the people of Dubuque. Pauline is passionate about improving her community, serving on several boards and committees. Part of that passion comes from the fact that she has overcome many obstacles in her personal life, and has always wanted to give the way people have given to help her through tough times. When she's not working or volunteering, she's spending time with her family and attending local events. Pauline and her husband, Brian, have three adult children and one teenager. She and her family attend Grand View Methodist Church. Donate to Chilton for Iowa Today!
description:
Pauline Chilton, the daughter of a Vietnam veteran, wife of a Gulf War veteran, grew up in Chicago and has been proud to call Dubuque home for the last 18 years. 

 

After graduating from Kenwood Academy, one of Chicago's three magnet schools, she attended Beloit College. During her academic career, she enjoyed studying chemistry, biochemistry, German, Japanese, and Brazilian Portuguese. She worked on her own chemistry research with the privilege of using facilities at the University of Chicago and Argonne National Laboratory. She was granted numerous awards and scholarships for participating in academic competitions and her work in chemistry. She did an internship in a biochemistry laboratory at Rush Presbyterian Medical Center.

 

A full time Realtor, Pauline has the perfect combination of the Midwestern attitude of hard work and dedication along with big city tenacity in order to facilitate smooth transactions for her clients. She feels that her real estate career has helped her to understand the needs of the people of Dubuque.

 

Pauline is passionate about improving her community, serving on several boards and committees. Part of that passion comes from the fact that she has overcome many obstacles in her personal life, and has always wanted to give the way people have given to help her through tough times. When she's not working or volunteering, she's spending time with her family and attending local events. Pauline and her husband, Brian, have three adult children and one teenager. She and her family attend Grand View Methodist Church.

Donate to Chilton for Iowa Today!

name: State Representative - 74th House District
text: Kansas truly is the land of opportunity. In 2018, I was elected to represent the 74th House District in the Kansas Legislature. As a result, I have had the opportunity to help Kansas rethink the way we do businesses. Being an entrepreneur allows me to bring a unique perspective the Capitol. I remind myself often that: Politics does not have to be political, common sense doesn't end at the front door and you can be passionate about a topic, but still be willing to listen and understand all perspectives. I currently serve on the following committees: Appropriations Judiciary Corrections / Juvenile Justice As a conservative Republican, I believe in personal accounatability, controlled spending, limited government and our fundamental rights as written in the Constitution and Bill of Rights. Now more than ever, we need people willing to stand firm on their principals and values. As we move through 2020, its once again election time. Fundraising is one of the biggest challenges for any elected official, however, it is absolutely the most crucial in getting the word out. I would appreciate any support you are willing to contribute.
description:
Kansas truly is the land of opportunity.  In 2018, I was elected to represent the 74th House District in the Kansas Legislature.  As a result, I have had the opportunity to help Kansas rethink the way we do businesses.  Being an entrepreneur allows me to bring a unique perspective the Capitol.  I remind myself often that: Politics does not have to be political, common sense doesn't end at the front door and you can be passionate about a topic, but still be willing to listen and understand all perspectives.  

I currently serve on the following committees:

  • Appropriations
  • Judiciary
  • Corrections / Juvenile Justice

    As a conservative Republican, I believe in personal accounatability, controlled spending, limited government and our fundamental rights as written in the Constitution and Bill of Rights.  

    Now more than ever, we need people willing to stand firm on their principals and values.  As we move through 2020, its once again election time.  Fundraising is one of the biggest challenges for any elected official, however, it is absolutely the most crucial in getting the word out.  I would appreciate any support you are willing to contribute.

name: Dan Fister For State Representative
text: My name is Dan Fister, and I am running for the Kentucky House of Representatives in the 56th District. This district includes part of Franklin County, part of Fayette County, and all of Woodford County. I am a Pro-God, Pro-Life candidate that believes very strongly in the U.S. Constitution. Including the Second Amendment and your right to keep and bear arms. My decision to run for public office was not taken lightly. I am not a politician and truly never considered such a path until I was asked and encouraged by several leaders in our community. As a farmer, property manager, and retired general contractor I have developed the skills necessary to make a positive difference in our community and in our state. It is truly time that you receive the representation you deserve and we start solving our problems rather than ignoring them.
description:
My name is Dan Fister, and I am running for the Kentucky House of Representatives in the 56th District. This district includes part of Franklin County, part of Fayette County, and all of Woodford County.

I am a Pro-God, Pro-Life candidate that believes very strongly in the U.S. Constitution. Including the Second Amendment and your right to keep and bear arms.

name: Haley For House
text: It has been an honor and a privilege to serve our community. I’m proud of all that we have accomplished on behalf of all Minnesotan’s over the past two years. We’ve passed major legislation to address rising healthcare costs, deliver the largest tax cut in nearly two decades, and increase funding for education and transportation.<U+200B>Throughout my first term, I have maintained my commitment to listen, learn the facts, respond to constituent concerns and needs, and help break down the barriers when “government gets in the way.” I have worked with many of you on local issues, such as health care and dredging in Wabasha, repayment from MNDot for Hwy 61 cost overruns and construction and repair projects in Red Wing, promotion of long term economic development plans for Lake City, and removing barriers for economic development plans in Cannon Falls and Welch. I’ve also been successful in securing bonding monies for the National Eagle Center in Wabasha, the Port Authority Assistance Fund, the Levee wall reconstruction in Red Wing, the Sheldon Theatre, the Mississippi Blufflands Trail, and the Goodhue County Historical Society. I have focused my energy and time in St. Paul on issues that are important to you and our region: affordable and accessible health care, a sustainable agricultural economy, strong schools and career preparedeness for our students, and lower taxes for our small business owners and middle-class families. Donate to Barb Haley for House Today!

text: Donate to Dave Bronson for Mayor Today! Anchorage, Alaska is home to Dave Bronson after a two year corporate commitment that turned into a love for Alaska lasting 29 years and counting! Born June 26, 1958 in Superior, Wisconsin, Dave earned his Bachelor of Science Degree in Agricultural Economics from the University of Wisconsin. After graduation, he was an Active Duty Air Force Pilot from 1981 to 1990, USAF Reserves Plans Officer from 1992 to 1993, and an Alaska ANG Maintenance Officer and Pilot from 1993 to 2005 while balancing a commercial airline pilot career from 1990 to 2020. While flying military aircraft, he met and married Debra. They have been married for 35 years and have raised two children, Katie and Zach. His love for The Last Frontier includes land, air, and water as he enjoys exploring Alaska while hunting, fishing, and flying to remote areas.

name: Friends Of Nicholas Burlingame
text: Anti-Incinerator | Pro-Term Limits | Pro-Police Friends and Neighbors, Last July, I had my first encounter with the Village of Endicott Board of Trustees. They voted on a new law, which made it impossible for the trade-school I operate to continue to do business in the village. At that point, I started regularly attending board meetings and advocating for my staff and how beneficial we are for the local community and economy. Thankfully, over a short 5-month period we were able to get the issue resolved. Since then I have learned a lot about the Village Board and it triggered my sense of duty and obligation to run for public office. There was such a low public turnout that the board could vote on issues unchecked. The Trustees seemed out of touch with current times and reality. They appear to hold onto the idealistic view that IBM or another large corporation will someday come rescue Endicott. I soon realized, they did not represent me, my family, or my community. We must never forget our storied past, but we need to look to the future. We cannot sit idly by and wait for the next IBM to save Endicott. The change must start with us. When I started my campaign, I knew the odds of winning were low and not for lack of trying. I believed it would be next to impossible to unseat a local career politician who has sat on the Village Board of Trustees for twenty years. I originally had no intention of soliciting supporters for donations; my goal was simply to be a fierce challenger, push the issues that they choose to ignore, hold the board accountable, and make them remember why they ran for office in the first place. Since then, Endicott has changed. Complacency is a thing of the past; Endicott residents have had enough and are calling for action. There have been protests, marches, rallies, press conferences, yard sign movements, community action groups formed, local politicians have been negatively reflected in national news, and citizens are starting to hold elected officials accountable. The majority of our current board is so accustomed to not being questioned, they are silencing the public from speaking at meetings and hiding their heads in the sand. These actions cannot be tolerated. I will fight to restore our right to speak, I will fight for clean industry, I will fight for board term-limits, and I will never stop fighting for a family friendly Endicott. I could not do this without the support of my family, friends and community. Today, I ask for your financial support. Running for office can get expensive. Mailings, yard signs, flyers… none of them are free. I realize due to the pandemic that these are uncertain times, but this is also a turning point and a historic election for Endicott. I am hoping you might be willing to support my campaign with a donation of $100, $50 or even $25. I appreciate all of the inspiration, generous support and prayers. Now, on to November. Thank you, Nick
description:
Anti-Incinerator | Pro-Term Limits | Pro-Police  

Friends and Neighbors,

Last July, I had my first encounter with the Village of Endicott Board of Trustees.  They voted on a new law, which made it impossible for the trade-school I operate to continue to do business in the village.  At that point, I started regularly attending board meetings and advocating for my staff and how beneficial we are for the local community and economy.  Thankfully, over a short 5-month period we were able to get the issue resolved.

Since then I have learned a lot about the Village Board and it triggered my sense of duty and obligation to run for public office.  There was such a low public turnout that the board could vote on issues unchecked.  The Trustees seemed out of touch with current times and reality.  They appear to hold onto the idealistic view that IBM or another large corporation will someday come rescue Endicott.  I soon realized, they did not represent me, my family, or my community.  We must never forget our storied past, but we need to look to the future. We cannot sit idly by and wait for the next IBM to save Endicott. The change must start with us.

When I started my campaign, I knew the odds of winning were low and not for lack of trying.  I believed it would be next to impossible to unseat a local career politician who has sat on the Village Board of Trustees for twenty years. I originally had no intention of soliciting supporters for donations; my goal was simply to be a fierce challenger, push the issues that they choose to ignore, hold the board accountable, and make them remember why they ran for office in the first place.

Since then, Endicott has changed. Complacency is a thing of the past; Endicott residents have had enough and are calling for action.  There have been protests, marches, rallies, press conferences, yard sign movements, community action groups formed, local politicians have been negatively reflected in national news, and citizens are starting to hold elected officials accountable.

The majority of our current board is so accustomed to not being questioned, they are silencing the public from speaking at meetings and hiding their heads in the sand. These actions cannot be tolerated. I will fight to restore our right to speak, I will fight for clean industry, I will fight for board term-limits, and I will never stop fighting for a family friendly Endicott.  

I could not do this without the support of my family, friends and community. Today, I ask for your financial support.  Running for office can get expensive.  Mailings, yard signs, flyers… none of them are free.  I realize due to the pandemic that these are uncertain times, but this is also a turning point and a historic election for Endicott.  I am hoping you might be willing to support my campaign with a donation of $100, $50 or even $25. I appreciate all of the inspiration, generous support and prayers.  Now, on to November.

Thank you,

Nick

name: Colbert County Republican Executive Committee
text: Join the Colbert County Republican Party at the Tuscumbia Railroad Roundhouse for our Constitution Day Celebration 2020, celebrating the 233rd anniversary of the United States Constitution. Join us Saturday, September 19th. Doors are open 5-9pm. Music comes from FAME recording artist James LeBlanc and Angela Hacker. Catfish and chicken dinners are provided by Swamp John’s while you hear from all of our local Republican Candidates. Local Republican candidates David Isom, Darol Bendall, Jackie Witt, and Chris Hand will all be there, and the keynote address will be delivered by Alabama Secretary of State John Merrill. • A donation of $25 gets you one ticket to Constitution Day 2020 activities and a delicious Swamp John’s catfish or chicken dinner. • Donate $500 and become a gold sponsor. Your company’s banner will be displayed prominently during the ceremony and on all CCREC social media. Sponsors will receive 8 individual tickets with preferred seating. • Donate $1,000 and become a co-host. Co-host’s graphics/logos will be featured in all event literature and placed prominently for all official ceremony photos. Co-hosts may choose to be introduced for remarks during the event live-stream on Facebook to more than 1,000 members. Co-hosts will receive 8 individual tickets with preferred seating. For more information, contact Chairman Phillip Green Phone: 256-762-4072 Email: [email protected] Checks can be mailed to: PO Box 4201 Muscle Shoals, AL 35661 Remember, this is a casual event. Come as you are and you'll fit right in. Donations support the work of work of the Colbert County Republican Party and our support of local Republican candidates.
description:
Join the Colbert County Republican Party at the Tuscumbia Railroad Roundhouse for our Constitution Day Celebration 2020, celebrating the 233rd anniversary of the United States Constitution.

Join us Saturday, September 19th.  Doors are open 5-9pm.  Music comes from FAME recording artist James LeBlanc and Angela Hacker. 

Catfish and chicken dinners are provided by Swamp John’s while you hear from all of our local Republican Candidates.

Local Republican candidates David Isom, Darol Bendall, Jackie Witt, and Chris Hand will all be there, and the keynote address will be delivered by Alabama Secretary of State John Merrill.

•             A donation of $25 gets you one ticket to Constitution Day 2020 activities and a delicious Swamp John’s catfish or chicken dinner.

•             Donate $500 and become a gold sponsor.  Your company’s banner will be displayed prominently during the ceremony and on all CCREC social media.  Sponsors will receive 8 individual tickets with preferred seating.

•             Donate $1,000 and become a co-host.  Co-host’s graphics/logos will be featured in all event literature and placed prominently for all official ceremony photos.  Co-hosts may choose to be introduced for remarks during the event live-stream on Facebook to more than 1,000 members.  Co-hosts will receive 8 individual tickets with preferred seating.

For more information, contact Chairman Phillip Green

Phone:  256-762-4072

Email:  colbertgopchair@pm.me

Checks can be mailed to:

PO Box 4201

Muscle Shoals, AL  35661

Remember, this is a casual event.  Come as you are and you'll fit right in.

Donations support the work of work of the Colbert County Republican Party and our support of local Republican candidates.

However, The New Mexico Voter Action Act does allow our committee to collect small donations from registered New Mexico voters of up to $100 per person. These donations will allow our campaign to reach more voters across the state of New Mexico. Per the Judicial Code of Conduct, candidates may not solicit donations or have knowledge of the donors to this page, contributions are monitored by Committee to Elect Kerry J. Morris to New Mexico Supreme Court.

Our job is to recruit, train, and mobilize the next generation of Republican leadership. We work together with fellow conservative organizations to bring the values of the Republican party to college campuses. Through activism and training, we are bringing new voters into the Republican party and educating them about our values. We connect students with national and in-state candidates so they can learn about those who represent them. Donate to the Texas Federation of College Republicans today!
